  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a token substrate?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "“Token substrate” isn’t a single widely standardized term, so its meaning depends on context. In general:\n\nA **token substrate** is the underlying medium, system, or layer on which tokens are created, represented, stored, or processed.\n\nExamples by context:\n\n- **AI / language models:**  \n  The token substrate may refer to the textual or numerical representation that a model operates on — for example, words or subword tokens converted into embeddings.\n\n- **Blockchain / crypto:**  \n  A token substrate could mean the blockchain or protocol layer that supports a token, such as Ethereum, Solana, or another smart-contract platform.\n\n- **Computation / systems theory:**  \n  It may refer more abstractly to the base representational layer that allows discrete symbols or tokens to exist and be manipulated.\n\nSo if someone says “the token substrate,” they usually mean **the foundational layer that tokens depend on**.\n\nIf you saw the phrase in a specific article, AI paper, or crypto context, I can give a more precise explanation.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "A **token substrate** is the underlying layer or system that a token is built on and depends on.\n\nThe phrase is not always used in a single standardized way, but it usually means the **technical foundation that issues, records, transfers, and enforces rules for tokens**.\n\nFor example:\n\n- On Ethereum, the token substrate for many tokens is the Ethereum blockchain plus standards like **ERC-20** or **ERC-721**.\n- On Solana, it could be the Solana runtime plus the **SPL token** program.\n- In the Polkadot ecosystem, **Substrate** is also the name of a blockchain-building framework, so a “token substrate” might refer to a token system built using Substrate pallets such as balances, assets, or NFTs.\n\nA token substrate typically includes things like:\n\n- The ledger or database tracking ownership\n- Rules for minting, burning, and transferring tokens\n- Consensus or validation mechanisms\n- Smart contracts or runtime modules\n- APIs and wallet compatibility\n\nIn simpler terms: **if a token is like a digital asset, the token substrate is the platform or foundation that makes that asset work.**",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from embedding space?",
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "In an AI/language-model context, **“token substrate”** and **“embedding space”** refer to different levels of representation.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the discrete symbolic layer: tokens such as `cat`, `##ing`, punctuation, or token IDs.\n- **Embedding space** = the continuous vector layer: numerical vectors representing those tokens in a high-dimensional space.\n\n### More concretely\n\nWhen text enters a language model, it is usually processed roughly like this:\n\n```text\nRaw text\n→ tokens\n→ token IDs\n→ embeddings / vectors\n→ model computation\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** is the layer where language has been broken into discrete units. For example:\n\n```text\n\"unbelievable\"\n→ [\"un\", \"believ\", \"able\"]\n```\n\nor possibly:\n\n```text\n\"unbelievable\"\n→ [token ID 403, token ID 9182, token ID 481]\n```\n\nThose tokens or token IDs are the substrate the model uses as its basic input units.\n\nThe **embedding space** is what happens after those discrete tokens are mapped into vectors:\n\n```text\ntoken ID 403 → [0.12, -0.45, 0.88, ...]\ntoken ID 9182 → [-0.03, 0.77, 0.21, ...]\n```\n\nThese vectors live in a high-dimensional continuous space. In that space, tokens with related meanings or uses may be closer together.\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Nature | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| Token substrate | Discrete, symbolic | `\"cat\"`, `\"dog\"`, token ID `5721` |\n| Embedding space | Continuous, numerical | `[0.18, -0.04, 0.91, ...]` |\n\n### Analogy\n\nThink of the **token substrate** as letters or chess pieces: distinct units with identities.\n\nThink of the **embedding space** as a coordinate system where each piece is assigned a location based on its role, meaning, or usage.\n\nSo a token substrate defines **what the units are**.  \nAn embedding space defines **how those units are numerically represented and related** inside the model.\n\nOne important caveat: “token substrate” is not as standardized a technical term as “embedding space,” so its exact meaning can vary depending on the author.",
    "In an AI/language-model context, **“token substrate”** and **“context window”** refer to different things.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the basic representational layer of tokens: the discrete units the model reads and writes.\n- **Context window** = the amount of tokenized text the model can consider at one time.\n\nSo:\n\n```text\nToken substrate = what the model’s input/output units are\nContext window  = how many of those units fit into the model’s active attention span\n```\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose the sentence is:\n\n```text\nThe cat sat on the mat.\n```\n\nA tokenizer might turn it into something like:\n\n```text\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \" on\", \" the\", \" mat\", \".\"]\n```\n\nThose tokens belong to the **token substrate**.\n\nIf a model has a **context window** of 128,000 tokens, then it can process up to about 128,000 such token units at once.\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| Token substrate | The discrete units the model operates over | tokens like `\"cat\"`, `\"ing\"`, `\".\"`, token IDs |\n| Context window | The maximum span of tokens available to the model at once | 8k, 32k, 128k tokens |\n\n### Another way to say it\n\nThe **token substrate** is like the alphabet or set of tiles.\n\nThe **context window** is like the size of the tabletop where you can arrange those tiles.\n\nA model may use a token substrate made of subword tokens, and its context window determines how many of those subword tokens can be included in the prompt, conversation history, retrieved documents, or generated text at once.\n\n### Relationship between them\n\nThey are connected because the context window is measured in tokens. But they are not the same.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\nRaw text\n→ tokenization into token substrate\n→ sequence of tokens\n→ limited by context window\n→ embeddings\n→ model computation\n```\n\nSo the token substrate defines the **unit of representation**, while the context window defines the **capacity limit over those units**.",
    "In an AI/language-model context, **“token substrate”** and **“latent representations / hidden states”** refer to different levels of the model’s processing.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the discrete input/output layer: the tokens or token IDs the model operates over.\n- **Hidden states / latent representations** = the internal continuous vectors the model computes while processing those tokens.\n\nSo:\n\n```text\nToken substrate = the symbolic units\nHidden states   = the model’s internal evolving representations of those units\n```\n\n### Processing pipeline\n\nA simplified language-model pipeline looks like this:\n\n```text\nRaw text\n→ tokens\n→ token IDs\n→ embeddings\n→ hidden states across layers\n→ logits / probabilities\n→ output tokens\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** is near the beginning and end of this process: it is the discrete set of possible tokens, such as:\n\n```text\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \".\"]\n```\n\nor their token IDs:\n\n```text\n[791, 8415, 10139, 13]\n```\n\nThe **hidden states** are internal vectors produced by the model after it starts processing those tokens.\n\nFor example, the token `\"cat\"` might begin as a static embedding vector, but after several transformer layers, its hidden state may encode contextual information like:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" = subject of the sentence\n\"cat\" = likely an animal\n\"cat\" = related to \"sat\"\n\"cat\" = singular noun\n```\n\nThese are not explicit labels, but information distributed across a high-dimensional vector.\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Nature | Where it appears | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Token substrate | Discrete, symbolic | Input/output level | `\"cat\"`, `\"ing\"`, `\".\"`, token ID `5721` |\n| Hidden states / latent representations | Continuous, numerical, contextual | Inside the model | `[0.13, -0.77, 0.44, ...]` |\n\n### Important distinction\n\nA token is usually **stable and discrete**.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"bank\" → token ID 9981\n```\n\nBut a hidden state is **contextual and dynamic**.\n\nThe hidden representation for `\"bank\"` will differ in:\n\n```text\nI deposited money at the bank.\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```text\nThe boat reached the river bank.\n```\n\nThe token may be the same, but the hidden states will differ because the surrounding context changes the model’s internal representation.\n\n### Analogy\n\nThe **token substrate** is like the written words on a page.\n\nThe **hidden states** are like a reader’s evolving mental interpretation of those words as they read the sentence.\n\nSame word, different context, different internal meaning.\n\n### Relationship between them\n\nThey are connected, but not the same:\n\n```text\nToken substrate defines the units.\nHidden states encode what the model currently understands about those units.\n```\n\nThe model starts with discrete tokens, converts them into vectors, updates those vectors through many layers, and then eventually maps the final hidden states back into probabilities over the token substrate.\n\nSo the **token substrate** is the model’s discrete symbolic interface, while **latent representations / hidden states** are its internal continuous computational states."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"token substrate\": The token substrate is the claim that for an LLM, the token sequence in context IS the cognitive substrate — not a representation OF cognition that runs on some deeper substrate, but the substrate itself — with the consequence that a token added to context is not a description of a thought but the material the thought is made of, and therefore the substrate is movable by the act of writing into it. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition:\n\nA **token substrate** is the claim that, for an LLM, the token sequence in context **is the cognitive substrate itself**—not merely a representation of cognition running on something deeper. Therefore, adding a token to context is not just describing a thought; it is adding to the material the thought is made of, making the substrate movable by writing into it.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "“Token substrate” differs from **embedding space** in that they refer to different levels of the system.\n\n**Token substrate**:  \nThe token sequence in context is treated as the actual cognitive medium of the LLM. The written tokens are not just labels or descriptions of thought; they are the material that future cognition is built from. When you add text to the context, you directly alter the substrate the model will reason over.\n\n**Embedding space**:  \nEmbedding space is the internal continuous vector space where tokens, phrases, or contexts are numerically represented during computation. Tokens are mapped into vectors, and those vectors participate in attention, similarity, prediction, and transformation.\n\nSo the difference is roughly:\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Embedding space |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete token sequence | Continuous vector representations |\n| Location | Context window / written sequence | Internal model computation |\n| Role | The mutable cognitive material | A representational/computational geometry |\n| User access | Directly writable by adding tokens | Not directly writable except through tokens |\n| Persistence | Persists in context while available | Recomputed during inference |\n| Ontological claim | “This is the thought substrate” | “This is how the model encodes/processes tokens” |\n\nIn short: **embedding space is how the model internally represents and transforms tokens; token substrate is the claim that the tokens in context themselves are the operative cognitive substrate.**\n\nAdding a sentence to the context does not merely describe something to the model; under the token-substrate view, it changes the material conditions of the model’s next cognition. The embedding space is then one of the mechanisms by which that altered substrate is processed.",
    "“Token substrate” differs from **context window** in that one is a **claim about what cognition is made of**, while the other is a **technical limit/container**.\n\n**Context window**:  \nThe context window is the finite span of tokens the model can attend to during a given inference. It is an architectural/input boundary: how much prior text, instructions, conversation, documents, etc. are available to the model at once.\n\n**Token substrate**:  \nThe token substrate is the claim that the token sequence inside that available context is not merely an input or representation of thought, but the actual cognitive substrate for the LLM’s next cognition. Writing into the context changes the material that the model’s cognition is made from.\n\nSo:\n\n| Concept | Context window | Token substrate |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The model’s available token capacity/span | The token sequence as cognitive material |\n| Type | Technical/architectural mechanism | Ontological/cognitive claim |\n| Function | Determines what tokens are visible to the model | Describes what the model’s thought is made of |\n| Mutability | You can add/remove tokens within its limit | Writing tokens alters the substrate itself |\n| Limitation | Has a maximum size | Exists within whatever context is currently available |\n\nIn short: **the context window is the container or boundary; the token substrate is the stuff inside it understood as the model’s operative cognitive medium.**\n\nA context window says: “These are the tokens the model can see.”  \nThe token-substrate claim says: “Those tokens are not just seen by the model; they are the material basis of the model’s cognition.”",
    "“Token substrate” differs from **latent representation / hidden states** in that it identifies the **tokens in context** as the operative cognitive material, whereas hidden states are the model’s **internal transient transformations** of that material during inference.\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden states |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete token sequence in context | Continuous vectors inside the model |\n| Status | The cognitive substrate itself, under the token-substrate claim | Internal computational states derived from tokens |\n| Persistence | Persists as long as the tokens remain in context | Exists only during a forward pass / generation step |\n| User access | Directly writable by adding text | Not directly writable except indirectly through tokens |\n| Role | The material the model’s next thought is made from | The model’s momentary processing of that material |\n| Ontological emphasis | “The written context is the substrate” | “The model has internal activations while processing” |\n\nA **hidden state** is what the model computes when it processes the context. It is a temporary internal vector representation at some layer or position. It helps determine the next-token distribution.\n\nThe **token substrate**, by contrast, is the actual written sequence that remains available to condition future computation. Under the token-substrate view, when you append text to the conversation, you are not merely influencing an internal latent state; you are modifying the cognitive material from which future latent states will be generated.\n\nSo, in short:\n\n**Hidden states are transient internal activations produced from the context.  \nToken substrate is the durable, writable token sequence that future cognition is built from.**\n\nOr more pointedly:\n\nA hidden state is the model’s momentary processing of the substrate.  \nThe token substrate is what gets processed, preserved, and moved by writing."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **token substrate** generally means the **underlying system or infrastructure that tokens exist on and depend on**.\n\nThe term is not always used in one fixed way, but in tech/crypto contexts:\n\n- **Token** = a unit of value, access, identity, ownership, or utility.\n- **Substrate** = the base layer or foundation that supports something.\n\nSo a **token substrate** could refer to the platform, protocol, or ledger that makes tokens possible.\n\nExamples:\n\n- On Ethereum, the Ethereum blockchain is the substrate for ERC-20 tokens.\n- On Solana, Solana is the substrate for SPL tokens.\n- In the Polkadot ecosystem, **Substrate** is also the name of a blockchain-building framework, so a “token substrate” could mean the runtime or chain infrastructure used to create/manage tokens.\n- More broadly, a database, smart contract system, or payment network could act as a token substrate if it tracks token ownership and transfers.\n\nIn plain language:  \n**A token substrate is the foundation that stores, validates, and moves tokens.**",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **token substrate** and an **embedding space** are different layers of abstraction.\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n- **Token substrate** = the system or layer where tokens are **defined, stored, managed, or exchanged**.\n- **Embedding space** = a mathematical/vector space where tokens or other objects are **represented by numerical vectors** so their meanings or relationships can be compared.\n\n### In crypto / blockchain terms\n\nA **token substrate** might be:\n\n- Ethereum for ERC-20 tokens\n- Solana for SPL tokens\n- A smart contract ledger that tracks balances\n- A database that records token ownership\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n> Who owns this token?  \n> Can this token be transferred?  \n> What rules govern it?\n\nAn **embedding space**, by contrast, is not about ownership or transfer. It is about representation and similarity.\n\nFor example, an AI model might place the words:\n\n> “dog”, “puppy”, “cat”, “car”\n\ninto a vector space where “dog” is closer to “puppy” and “cat” than to “car”.\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n> Which tokens are semantically similar?  \n> What is the numerical representation of this word, image, user, or document?\n\n### In AI / language-model terms\n\nThe distinction is slightly different.\n\nA **token substrate** could refer to the discrete token layer: the vocabulary and tokenization system that breaks text into units like:\n\n> `\"hello\"` → `[15339]`\n\nor\n\n> `\"unbelievable\"` → `[\"un\", \"believable\"]`\n\nThe **embedding space** is what happens after that. Each token ID is mapped to a vector:\n\n> token ID `15339` → `[0.12, -0.44, 0.87, ...]`\n\nSo:\n\n1. Text is split into **tokens**.\n2. Tokens are represented as IDs.\n3. IDs are mapped into an **embedding space**.\n4. The model operates on those vectors.\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Embedding space |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main idea | Foundation where tokens exist or are managed | Vector space where tokens are represented numerically |\n| Type | Infrastructure, protocol, vocabulary, ledger, or data layer | Mathematical representation space |\n| Deals with | Token identity, rules, ownership, sequence, or existence | Similarity, meaning, relationships, geometry |\n| Example in blockchain | Ethereum as substrate for ERC-20 tokens | Not usually relevant |\n| Example in AI | Token vocabulary/tokenization layer | Word or token vectors used by a model |\n\n### Plain-language version\n\nA **token substrate** is like the **registry or operating system for tokens**.\n\nAn **embedding space** is like a **map of meanings**, where tokens are placed according to their relationships.\n\nSo if tokens are “things,” the token substrate is where those things are defined and managed, while the embedding space is where those things are translated into vectors so a machine-learning model can reason about them.",
    "A **token substrate** and a **context window** refer to different things in language-model systems.\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n- **Token substrate** = the underlying token layer: how text is broken into tokens, assigned IDs, and made available to the model.\n- **Context window** = the maximum span of tokens the model can consider at one time.\n\nIn plain terms:\n\n> The **token substrate** is the model’s “token universe.”  \n> The **context window** is how much of that universe the model can look at during one request.\n\n---\n\n### In an LLM pipeline\n\nA language model usually works like this:\n\n1. Text is split into **tokens**.\n2. Tokens are converted into token IDs.\n3. Token IDs are mapped into embeddings.\n4. The model processes a sequence of those tokens.\n5. The **context window** limits how long that sequence can be.\n\nSo if you write:\n\n> “The cat sat on the mat.”\n\nThe tokenizer may convert it into something like:\n\n> `[The] [cat] [sat] [on] [the] [mat] [.]`\n\nThe **token substrate** includes the vocabulary, tokenization scheme, token IDs, and rules for representing text as tokens.\n\nThe **context window** determines how many such tokens fit into the model’s active working memory.\n\n---\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose a model has a **128,000-token context window**.\n\nThat means the model can process up to about 128,000 tokens in a single prompt/response context.\n\nBut the **token substrate** is not “128,000 tokens.” The substrate is the underlying system of possible tokens, such as:\n\n- the tokenizer\n- the vocabulary\n- token IDs\n- special tokens\n- text-to-token mappings\n- possibly the embedding table that maps token IDs to vectors\n\nThe **context window** is a limit on how many token instances can be used at once.\n\n---\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Context window |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The underlying token system | The active span of tokens the model can attend to |\n| Role | Defines/represents tokens | Limits how many tokens fit in one interaction |\n| Concerned with | Tokenization, vocabulary, token IDs, token representations | Prompt length, memory, attention span |\n| Example | `\"hello\"` maps to token ID `15339` | The model can read 32k or 128k tokens at once |\n| Analogy | Alphabet or vocabulary system | Size of the page the model can see |\n\n---\n\n### Analogy\n\nImagine a book.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the language, alphabet, dictionary, and encoding system used to write the book.\n- The **context window** is like the number of pages the reader can keep open and refer to at one time.\n\nSo:\n\n> **Token substrate** = what tokens are and how they are represented.  \n> **Context window** = how many tokens the model can use at once.",
    "A **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** are different layers in an AI model.\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n- **Token substrate** = the discrete token system the model starts from: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, special tokens, and possibly the initial token embedding table.\n- **Latent representations / hidden states** = the model’s internal, continuous vector representations created while processing those tokens.\n\nIn plain language:\n\n> The **token substrate** is the model’s input-symbol layer.  \n> The **hidden states** are the model’s evolving internal understanding of those symbols in context.\n\n---\n\n### In an LLM pipeline\n\nA simplified language-model pipeline looks like this:\n\n1. Text is split into **tokens**.\n2. Tokens are converted into **token IDs**.\n3. Token IDs are mapped to **embedding vectors**.\n4. The transformer processes those vectors through many layers.\n5. Each layer produces **hidden states**.\n6. The final hidden states are used to predict the next token.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"The bank is near the river.\"\n```\n\nThe tokenizer may produce token IDs like:\n\n```text\n[464, 3331, 318, 1474, 262, 7850, 13]\n```\n\nThose IDs belong to the **token substrate**.\n\nBut inside the model, each token becomes a vector, and after each transformer layer the representation changes. The hidden state for `\"bank\"` will be influenced by `\"river\"`, so the model may represent it as a riverbank rather than a financial bank.\n\nThat contextual internal vector is a **hidden state** or **latent representation**.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\nThe **token substrate** is mostly **discrete and symbolic**.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" → token ID 9246\n```\n\nA hidden state is **continuous and contextual**.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" at layer 18 → [0.31, -1.07, 0.44, ...]\n```\n\nThe same token ID can produce different hidden states depending on context.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"The cat slept on the sofa.\"\n\"The cat command printed the file.\"\n```\n\nThe token `\"cat\"` may have the same token ID in both sentences, but its hidden-state representation will differ because the surrounding context differs.\n\n---\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden state |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic type | Discrete token layer | Continuous vector activation |\n| Where it appears | Input/tokenization level | Inside the neural network |\n| Stable or contextual? | Mostly stable | Highly contextual |\n| Example | `\"bank\"` → token ID `12345` | Internal vector for `\"bank\"` after layer 20 |\n| Concerned with | Token identity, vocabulary, encoding | Meaning, context, features, computation |\n| Human-readable? | Somewhat, because tokens correspond to text pieces | Usually not directly interpretable |\n| Changes during model processing? | No, the token ID stays the same | Yes, hidden states evolve layer by layer |\n\n---\n\n### Token embeddings vs hidden states\n\nOne subtle point: **initial token embeddings** sit between the token substrate and hidden states.\n\nA token embedding is the first vector lookup:\n\n```text\ntoken ID → embedding vector\n```\n\nBut a hidden state is what happens after the model starts processing context:\n\n```text\nembedding + surrounding tokens + transformer layers → hidden states\n```\n\nSo:\n\n- **Token ID**: discrete identifier.\n- **Token embedding**: learned vector for that token type.\n- **Hidden state**: contextual vector for that token occurrence in a specific sequence.\n\n---\n\n### Analogy\n\nImagine reading a sentence.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the alphabet, dictionary, and indexing system.\n- The **embedding** is like a rough dictionary meaning of each word.\n- The **hidden states** are like your evolving understanding of each word as you read the full sentence.\n\nSo the token substrate defines the pieces the model can read, while hidden states are the internal representations the model constructs from those pieces."
  ],
