        "assistant": "“Token substrate” isn’t a single widely standardized term, so its meaning depends on context. In general:\n\nA **token substrate** is the underlying medium, system, or layer on which tokens are created, represented, stored, or processed.\n\nExamples by context:\n\n- **AI / language models:**  \n  The token substrate may refer to the textual or numerical representation that a model operates on — for example, words or subword tokens converted into embeddings.\n\n- **Blockchain / crypto:**  \n  A token substrate could mean the blockchain or protocol layer that supports a token, such as Ethereum, Solana, or another smart-contract platform.\n\n- **Computation / systems theory:**  \n  It may refer more abstractly to the base representational layer that allows discrete symbols or tokens to exist and be manipulated.\n\nSo if someone says “the token substrate,” they usually mean **the foundational layer that tokens depend on**.\n\nIf you saw the phrase in a specific article, AI paper, or crypto context, I can give a more precise explanation.",
