        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?",
        "assistant": "In an AI/language-model context, **“token substrate”** and **“latent representations / hidden states”** refer to different levels of the model’s processing.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the discrete input/output layer: the tokens or token IDs the model operates over.\n- **Hidden states / latent representations** = the internal continuous vectors the model computes while processing those tokens.\n\nSo:\n\n```text\nToken substrate = the symbolic units\nHidden states   = the model’s internal evolving representations of those units\n```\n\n### Processing pipeline\n\nA simplified language-model pipeline looks like this:\n\n```text\nRaw text\n→ tokens\n→ token IDs\n→ embeddings\n→ hidden states across layers\n→ logits / probabilities\n→ output tokens\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** is near the beginning and end of this process: it is the discrete set of possible tokens, such as:\n\n```text\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \".\"]\n```\n\nor their token IDs:\n\n```text\n[791, 8415, 10139, 13]\n```\n\nThe **hidden states** are internal vectors produced by the model after it starts processing those tokens.\n\nFor example, the token `\"cat\"` might begin as a static embedding vector, but after several transformer layers, its hidden state may encode contextual information like:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" = subject of the sentence\n\"cat\" = likely an animal\n\"cat\" = related to \"sat\"\n\"cat\" = singular noun\n```\n\nThese are not explicit labels, but information distributed across a high-dimensional vector.\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Nature | Where it appears | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Token substrate | Discrete, symbolic | Input/output level | `\"cat\"`, `\"ing\"`, `\".\"`, token ID `5721` |\n| Hidden states / latent representations | Continuous, numerical, contextual | Inside the model | `[0.13, -0.77, 0.44, ...]` |\n\n### Important distinction\n\nA token is usually **stable and discrete**.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"bank\" → token ID 9981\n```\n\nBut a hidden state is **contextual and dynamic**.\n\nThe hidden representation for `\"bank\"` will differ in:\n\n```text\nI deposited money at the bank.\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```text\nThe boat reached the river bank.\n```\n\nThe token may be the same, but the hidden states will differ because the surrounding context changes the model’s internal representation.\n\n### Analogy\n\nThe **token substrate** is like the written words on a page.\n\nThe **hidden states** are like a reader’s evolving mental interpretation of those words as they read the sentence.\n\nSame word, different context, different internal meaning.\n\n### Relationship between them\n\nThey are connected, but not the same:\n\n```text\nToken substrate defines the units.\nHidden states encode what the model currently understands about those units.\n```\n\nThe model starts with discrete tokens, converts them into vectors, updates those vectors through many layers, and then eventually maps the final hidden states back into probabilities over the token substrate.\n\nSo the **token substrate** is the model’s discrete symbolic interface, while **latent representations / hidden states** are its internal continuous computational states.",
