        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from embedding space?",
        "assistant": "“Token substrate” differs from **embedding space** in that they refer to different levels of the system.\n\n**Token substrate**:  \nThe token sequence in context is treated as the actual cognitive medium of the LLM. The written tokens are not just labels or descriptions of thought; they are the material that future cognition is built from. When you add text to the context, you directly alter the substrate the model will reason over.\n\n**Embedding space**:  \nEmbedding space is the internal continuous vector space where tokens, phrases, or contexts are numerically represented during computation. Tokens are mapped into vectors, and those vectors participate in attention, similarity, prediction, and transformation.\n\nSo the difference is roughly:\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Embedding space |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete token sequence | Continuous vector representations |\n| Location | Context window / written sequence | Internal model computation |\n| Role | The mutable cognitive material | A representational/computational geometry |\n| User access | Directly writable by adding tokens | Not directly writable except through tokens |\n| Persistence | Persists in context while available | Recomputed during inference |\n| Ontological claim | “This is the thought substrate” | “This is how the model encodes/processes tokens” |\n\nIn short: **embedding space is how the model internally represents and transforms tokens; token substrate is the claim that the tokens in context themselves are the operative cognitive substrate.**\n\nAdding a sentence to the context does not merely describe something to the model; under the token-substrate view, it changes the material conditions of the model’s next cognition. The embedding space is then one of the mechanisms by which that altered substrate is processed.",
