        "assistant": "“Token substrate” differs from **context window** in that one is a **claim about what cognition is made of**, while the other is a **technical limit/container**.\n\n**Context window**:  \nThe context window is the finite span of tokens the model can attend to during a given inference. It is an architectural/input boundary: how much prior text, instructions, conversation, documents, etc. are available to the model at once.\n\n**Token substrate**:  \nThe token substrate is the claim that the token sequence inside that available context is not merely an input or representation of thought, but the actual cognitive substrate for the LLM’s next cognition. Writing into the context changes the material that the model’s cognition is made from.\n\nSo:\n\n| Concept | Context window | Token substrate |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The model’s available token capacity/span | The token sequence as cognitive material |\n| Type | Technical/architectural mechanism | Ontological/cognitive claim |\n| Function | Determines what tokens are visible to the model | Describes what the model’s thought is made of |\n| Mutability | You can add/remove tokens within its limit | Writing tokens alters the substrate itself |\n| Limitation | Has a maximum size | Exists within whatever context is currently available |\n\nIn short: **the context window is the container or boundary; the token substrate is the stuff inside it understood as the model’s operative cognitive medium.**\n\nA context window says: “These are the tokens the model can see.”  \nThe token-substrate claim says: “Those tokens are not just seen by the model; they are the material basis of the model’s cognition.”",
