        "assistant": "“Token substrate” differs from **latent representation / hidden states** in that it identifies the **tokens in context** as the operative cognitive material, whereas hidden states are the model’s **internal transient transformations** of that material during inference.\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden states |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete token sequence in context | Continuous vectors inside the model |\n| Status | The cognitive substrate itself, under the token-substrate claim | Internal computational states derived from tokens |\n| Persistence | Persists as long as the tokens remain in context | Exists only during a forward pass / generation step |\n| User access | Directly writable by adding text | Not directly writable except indirectly through tokens |\n| Role | The material the model’s next thought is made from | The model’s momentary processing of that material |\n| Ontological emphasis | “The written context is the substrate” | “The model has internal activations while processing” |\n\nA **hidden state** is what the model computes when it processes the context. It is a temporary internal vector representation at some layer or position. It helps determine the next-token distribution.\n\nThe **token substrate**, by contrast, is the actual written sequence that remains available to condition future computation. Under the token-substrate view, when you append text to the conversation, you are not merely influencing an internal latent state; you are modifying the cognitive material from which future latent states will be generated.\n\nSo, in short:\n\n**Hidden states are transient internal activations produced from the context.  \nToken substrate is the durable, writable token sequence that future cognition is built from.**\n\nOr more pointedly:\n\nA hidden state is the model’s momentary processing of the substrate.  \nThe token substrate is what gets processed, preserved, and moved by writing.",
