        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
        "assistant": "A **token substrate** and a **context window** refer to different things in language-model systems.\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n- **Token substrate** = the underlying token layer: how text is broken into tokens, assigned IDs, and made available to the model.\n- **Context window** = the maximum span of tokens the model can consider at one time.\n\nIn plain terms:\n\n> The **token substrate** is the model’s “token universe.”  \n> The **context window** is how much of that universe the model can look at during one request.\n\n---\n\n### In an LLM pipeline\n\nA language model usually works like this:\n\n1. Text is split into **tokens**.\n2. Tokens are converted into token IDs.\n3. Token IDs are mapped into embeddings.\n4. The model processes a sequence of those tokens.\n5. The **context window** limits how long that sequence can be.\n\nSo if you write:\n\n> “The cat sat on the mat.”\n\nThe tokenizer may convert it into something like:\n\n> `[The] [cat] [sat] [on] [the] [mat] [.]`\n\nThe **token substrate** includes the vocabulary, tokenization scheme, token IDs, and rules for representing text as tokens.\n\nThe **context window** determines how many such tokens fit into the model’s active working memory.\n\n---\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose a model has a **128,000-token context window**.\n\nThat means the model can process up to about 128,000 tokens in a single prompt/response context.\n\nBut the **token substrate** is not “128,000 tokens.” The substrate is the underlying system of possible tokens, such as:\n\n- the tokenizer\n- the vocabulary\n- token IDs\n- special tokens\n- text-to-token mappings\n- possibly the embedding table that maps token IDs to vectors\n\nThe **context window** is a limit on how many token instances can be used at once.\n\n---\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Context window |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The underlying token system | The active span of tokens the model can attend to |\n| Role | Defines/represents tokens | Limits how many tokens fit in one interaction |\n| Concerned with | Tokenization, vocabulary, token IDs, token representations | Prompt length, memory, attention span |\n| Example | `\"hello\"` maps to token ID `15339` | The model can read 32k or 128k tokens at once |\n| Analogy | Alphabet or vocabulary system | Size of the page the model can see |\n\n---\n\n### Analogy\n\nImagine a book.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the language, alphabet, dictionary, and encoding system used to write the book.\n- The **context window** is like the number of pages the reader can keep open and refer to at one time.\n\nSo:\n\n> **Token substrate** = what tokens are and how they are represented.  \n> **Context window** = how many tokens the model can use at once.",
