      {
        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?",
        "assistant": "A **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** are different layers in an AI model.\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n- **Token substrate** = the discrete token system the model starts from: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, special tokens, and possibly the initial token embedding table.\n- **Latent representations / hidden states** = the model’s internal, continuous vector representations created while processing those tokens.\n\nIn plain language:\n\n> The **token substrate** is the model’s input-symbol layer.  \n> The **hidden states** are the model’s evolving internal understanding of those symbols in context.\n\n---\n\n### In an LLM pipeline\n\nA simplified language-model pipeline looks like this:\n\n1. Text is split into **tokens**.\n2. Tokens are converted into **token IDs**.\n3. Token IDs are mapped to **embedding vectors**.\n4. The transformer processes those vectors through many layers.\n5. Each layer produces **hidden states**.\n6. The final hidden states are used to predict the next token.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"The bank is near the river.\"\n```\n\nThe tokenizer may produce token IDs like:\n\n```text\n[464, 3331, 318, 1474, 262, 7850, 13]\n```\n\nThose IDs belong to the **token substrate**.\n\nBut inside the model, each token becomes a vector, and after each transformer layer the representation changes. The hidden state for `\"bank\"` will be influenced by `\"river\"`, so the model may represent it as a riverbank rather than a financial bank.\n\nThat contextual internal vector is a **hidden state** or **latent representation**.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\nThe **token substrate** is mostly **discrete and symbolic**.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" → token ID 9246\n```\n\nA hidden state is **continuous and contextual**.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" at layer 18 → [0.31, -1.07, 0.44, ...]\n```\n\nThe same token ID can produce different hidden states depending on context.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"The cat slept on the sofa.\"\n\"The cat command printed the file.\"\n```\n\nThe token `\"cat\"` may have the same token ID in both sentences, but its hidden-state representation will differ because the surrounding context differs.\n\n---\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden state |\n|---|---|---|\n| Basic type | Discrete token layer | Continuous vector activation |\n| Where it appears | Input/tokenization level | Inside the neural network |\n| Stable or contextual? | Mostly stable | Highly contextual |\n| Example | `\"bank\"` → token ID `12345` | Internal vector for `\"bank\"` after layer 20 |\n| Concerned with | Token identity, vocabulary, encoding | Meaning, context, features, computation |\n| Human-readable? | Somewhat, because tokens correspond to text pieces | Usually not directly interpretable |\n| Changes during model processing? | No, the token ID stays the same | Yes, hidden states evolve layer by layer |\n\n---\n\n### Token embeddings vs hidden states\n\nOne subtle point: **initial token embeddings** sit between the token substrate and hidden states.\n\nA token embedding is the first vector lookup:\n\n```text\ntoken ID → embedding vector\n```\n\nBut a hidden state is what happens after the model starts processing context:\n\n```text\nembedding + surrounding tokens + transformer layers → hidden states\n```\n\nSo:\n\n- **Token ID**: discrete identifier.\n- **Token embedding**: learned vector for that token type.\n- **Hidden state**: contextual vector for that token occurrence in a specific sequence.\n\n---\n\n### Analogy\n\nImagine reading a sentence.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the alphabet, dictionary, and indexing system.\n- The **embedding** is like a rough dictionary meaning of each word.\n- The **hidden states** are like your evolving understanding of each word as you read the full sentence.\n\nSo the token substrate defines the pieces the model can read, while hidden states are the internal representations the model constructs from those pieces.",
